http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Schools today must assist students in developing the necessary skills, intellectual abilities, and personal traits that help them to secure and maintain meaningful employment in the world of work. According to current labor projections, two-thirds of all jobs in the 21st century will be high skill, high technology in nature. The Wyoming Career/Vocational Education Standards Committee utilized the findings of the U.S. Department of Labor, Secretary's Commission on Achieving Necessary Skills (SCANS Report) and regional meetings to develop a framework for state standards.
Resources: Students effectively manage time, money, materials, work space, and human resources.
Students complete tasks within an allotted time.
Students are familiar with basic monetary skills.
Students acquire, store, organize, and use materials and space.
Students seek or provide help when appropriate (staff, students, parents, etc.).
Students plan tasks using specific timelines that take into account constraints, priorities, and goals.
Students demonstrate an understanding of financial information.
Students acquire, store, organize, and use materials and work space.
Students acknowledge and utilize individual skills and abilities.
Students prepare and analyze personal or business financial information.
Students assess individual skills, evaluate, and adjust their performance accordingly.
Students prioritize and manage time, materials, work space, and resources to set and achieve goals.
Interpersonal Skills: Students acquire and demonstrate interpersonal skills necessary to be successful in the workplace.
Students identify and practice compromise and conflict resolution skills.
Students share skills with others.
Students identify and actively participate in group roles and responsibilities.
Students recognize diversity in others.
Students develop skills to work effectively with diverse individuals/groups.
Students communicate using a variety of methods in the workplace setting.
Students participate as a member of a team to accomplish group goals.
Students share a learned skill.
Students work with individuals/groups of diverse abilities and backgrounds in a workplace setting.
Students communicate using a variety of methods in a workplace setting.
Students assume a leadership role in a group setting to accomplish group goals.
Students demonstrate and/or teach a learned skill.
Information: Students acquire and use workplace information.
Students identify a variety of sources that provide workplace information.
Students organize information using systematic methods (e.g. assignment book, alphabetizing, calendar, and database).
Students use a variety of methods to complete a task (e.g. oral, written, graphic, pictorial, and multimedia).
Students locate and use various sources of workplace information.
Students organize workplace information.
Students communicate workplace information in various formats.
Students acquire and evaluate workplace information.
Students organize and update workplace information.
Students interpret and communicate workplace information.
Students use technology to process workplace information.
Systems: Students demonstrate an understanding of how social, organizational, and technological systems work.
Students identify components of family, community, and school systems in everyday life.
Students explain the need for rules within organizational systems.
Students explain how systems operate and impact students' lives.
Students identify technical systems and explain how they are used in the workplace.
Students evaluate the quality and performance of a variety of systems.
Students suggest modifications to existing systems and develop new or alternative ideas for systems to improve performance.
Technology: Students demonstrate the ability to use a variety of workplace technologies.
Students identify technologies used in the workplace.
Students practice responsible use and care of technology.
Students demonstrate technical knowledge and skills using appropriate technologies.
Students apply safe and ethical practices in the workplace.
Students choose and utilize procedures, tools, or equipment, including computers and related technologies.
Students demonstrate proper procedure for set-up, operation, and routine maintenance of workplace equipment.
Students use workplace equipment to solve problems.
Students apply safe and ethical practices when using workplace technologies.
Careers: Students develop skills in career planning and workplace readiness.
Students identify various occupations.
Students describe how current learning relates to career options.
Students describe how work relates to meeting needs for goods, clothing, shelter, and other necessities for living.
Students identify behaviors that contribute to the successful completion of workplace tasks.
Students explore careers.
Students identify careers that align with individual strengths, interests, and coursework.
Students describe employability skills.
Students interpret information from a variety of self-assessments to identify career interests, abilities, personal traits, and work values.
Students locate and interpret career information and labor market trends from a variety of sources.
Students create, evaluate, and revise career plans.
Students demonstrate skills to seek, obtain, maintain, and change jobs.
